Step 1
#Elements Identified#:
Permutation of numbers from 1 to 200;  
Sum over 100 fixed pairs of positions with consecutive indices (e.g., (1,2), (3,4), ..., (199,200));  
Absolute difference operation;  
No weights or multipliers;  
Average over all possible permutations;  
Fixed number of elements (200) and terms (100);  
Theme: Expected value of a sum of absolute differences over permutations.

Step 2
#Plan#:
Modify pairing to non-consecutive positions with offset 2 in blocks;  
Change operation from absolute difference to squared difference;  
Introduce weighting by group index, multiplying each term by the block number;  
Maintain fixed structure (200 positions, 100 terms) and theme;  
All components interconnect via grouped pairs, squared terms, and weights increasing complexity through altered dependencies and variance computation.

Step 3
#Rewritten Instruction#:
A permutation of a list of numbers is an ordered arrangement of the numbers in that list. Determine the average value of

$$
\sum_{m=1}^{50} m \left[ \left( p_{4m-3} - p_{4m-1} \right)^2 + \left( p_{4m-2} - p_{4m} \right)^2 \right]
$$

over all permutations \( p_{1}, p_{2}, \ldots, p_{200} \) of \( 1,2,3,\ldots,199,200 \). (The sum consists of 100 terms, organized in 50 groups: for each \( m \), the group contributes squared differences for positions \( (4m-3, 4m-1) \) and \( (4m-2, 4m) \), each multiplied by \( m \).)

Step 4
#Finally Rewritten Instruction#:
A permutation of a list of numbers is an ordered arrangement of the numbers in that list. Determine the average value of

$$
\sum_{m=1}^{50} m \left[ \left( p_{4m-3} - p_{4m-1} \right)^2 + \left( p_{4m-2} - p_{4m} \right)^2 \right]
$$

over all permutations \( p_{1}, p_{2}, \ldots, p_{200} \) of \( 1,2,3,\ldots,199,200 \). (The sum contains 100 terms of the form squared differences, grouped into 50 blocks with weights.)

original_problem:
Suppose that, for some angles $x$ and $y$,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \sin ^{2} x+\cos ^{2} y=\frac{3}{2} a \\
& \cos ^{2} x+\sin ^{2} y=\frac{1}{2} a^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Determine the possible value(s) of $a$.
